{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionRemote sensing is a broad detection strategy that uses sensors to capture objects' electromagnetic wave properties and extract the object characteristics with their change regulations using data processing and analysis [1,2].",
    "Recently, remote sensing images have improved temporal, spatial, and spectral resolutions with the advancements in computer science and the expanding number of remote-sensing satellites.",
    "While traditional \"object-based\" and \"pixel-based\" classifications consider low-level features, the escalating quality and quantity of remote-sensing data necessitate an exploration of higher-level contextual information within images.",
    "The improvements in spatial, spectral, and temporal resolutions have resulted in a greater need to extract complex, high-level contextual information, as traditional methods relying on handcrafted features are unable to handle the increased complexity of remote sensing data.",
    "These advances have led to a shift toward deep learning methods, particularly CNNs, which can automatically learn abstract features and capture multi-scale, multi-dimensional relationships across different resolutions, making them more effective in processing HRRS data.Image classification based on remote sensing is a fundamental and vital part of remote sensing image processing and analysis by utilizing the upper-level semantic information in the images, and it is widely used in land resource management [3,4], military investigation, change detection, object detection [5][6][7][8], environmental monitoring [9][10][11][12], urban planning, and other fields."
  ]
}